3 Questions

3.1 1. What number of k did you select? Why?

I chose 3. On the total error plot, the biggest change in slope, or the elbow, would be at k = 3.

3.2 2. How many observations are there in each cluster?

253, 337, and 108.

3.3 3. Using the fviz_cluster() function, import here the original plot with k=4 did in class, and the new one with the number of k you selected for this exercise. How do they visually compare? Which one seems to be a better choice, and why?

Code 
library(tidyverse)

library(factoextra)

weather <- read_csv("../data/weather_monthsum.csv") %>%
  dplyr::select(-c(year:strength_gtex)) %>%
  mutate(across(everything(), ~scale(.x)))

mod_km4 <- kmeans(weather,
                  centers = 4,
                  nstart = 10)
mod_km3 <- kmeans(weather,
                  centers = 3,
                  nstart = 10)

fviz_cluster(mod_km4,
             data = weather)
Code 
fviz_cluster(mod_km3,
             data = weather)

Since I chose k = 3, there will be one less cluster than k = 4. This can be seen visually, as the cluster in the lower left in k = 4 is now absorbed by the lower center cluster in k = 4. Interestingly, though, observation 589 is clustered with the top right cluster in k = 3, but in k = 4 it is a part of the lower center cluster.

I believe that the k = 4 cluster is better, since all the clusters have a more rounded/ circular shape. In k = 3, the lower center cluster is very oblong, and there is a large gap in between what would two separate clusters in k = 4.
